See Harris-Bennett formula for basal energy

The HarrisBenedict equations revised by Mifflin and St Jeor in 1990:[4]

Men BMR = (10 weight in kg) + (6.25 height in cm) - (5 age in years) + 5 Women BMR = (10 weight in kg) + (6.25 height in cm) - (5 age in years) - 161

for me that would be 10 * pounds * 0.4536 + ( 6.25 * 69 * 2.54) - (5 * 70) + 5

bmr <- (10 * 146 * 0.4536) + ( 6.25 * 69 * 2.54) - (5 * 69) + 5
print(bmr)
[1] 1417.631
print(bmr * 1.76)
[1] 2495.031
bmr / (24 * 60 * 60) # calories per second
[1] 0.01640777

Apple Developer Guidelines Use motion data to offer a tangible benefit to the user. The gathering of motion data should offer a tangible benefit to the user. For example, fitness apps use the data to provide feedback about the users activity and general health. Do not record data simply to have the data.

guy became suspect because of fitness tracking https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/google-tracked-his-bike-ride-past-burglarized-home-made-him-n1151761

Lets look at workout and basal energy. Do totals agree.

y2020 <- intra4 %>% 
  filter(year(utc_start) == 2020, !is.na(workout_utc_start)) %>% 
  group_by(workout_utc_start, workout_utc_end) %>% 
  summarise(basal_sum = sum(value * (type == "BasalEnergyBurned"), na.rm = TRUE),
            active_sum = sum(value * (type == "ActiveEnergyBurned"), na.rm = TRUE),
            duration = last(duration)) %>% 
  left_join(workout_df %>% select(utc_start, utc_end, duration, totalEnergyBurned),
            by = c("workout_utc_start" = "utc_start", "workout_utc_end" = "utc_end"))
